Therefore, given the problem's lattice constant at 100°C, the density is approximately 8.66 g/cm³. **Final Answer** The density of copper at \(100^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\) is \boxed{8.66} \(g/cm^3\). </think> To find the density of copper at \(100^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\) given its lattice constant of \(3.655 \AA\): 1. **Volume of the unit cell**: - The lattice constant \(a = 3.655 \AA = 3.655 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{cm}\). - The volume \(V\) of the unit cell is \(a^3\): \[ V = (3.655 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{cm})^3 = 4.8727 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{cm}^3 \] 2. **Mass of the unit cell**: - Copper has a face-centered cubic (FCC) structure with 4 atoms per unit cell. - The atomic mass of copper is \(63.546 \, \text{g/mol}\). - The mass of one copper atom is \(\frac{63.546 \, \text{g/mol}}{6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{atoms/mol}} \approx 10.552 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{g}\). - The mass of 4 atoms is \(4 \times 10.552 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{g} \approx 42.208 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{g}\). 3. **Density calculation**: - Density \(\rho\) is given by \(\frac{\text{mass}}{\text{volume}}\): \[ \rho = \frac{42.208 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{g}}{4.8727 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{cm}^3} \approx 8.66 \, \text{g/cm}^3 \] Thus, the density of copper at \(100^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\) is \(\boxed{8.66}\) \(g/cm^3\).
